Pressurized sodium can be found in a wide variety of structures, many of them incommensurate ``host-guest'' composites (Gregoryanz, 2008): \begin{itemize} \item The ground state of sodium is \href{current_web_home_dir/A_cI2_229_a-001}{the body-centered cubic lattice ($A2$)}. \item Above 78K a metastable \href{current_web_home_dir/A_hP2_194_c-001}{hexagonal close-packed ($A3$) phase} has been observed. (Donohue, 1974) \item In the range 100-118 GPa and near room temperature sodium takes on the \href{current_web_home_dir/A_cI16_220_c-001}{high pressure cI16 lithium structure}. \item The current oP8 structure is stable in the range 118-125 GPa, again near room temperature. \end{itemize} ~ \vspace{-.25in} 
 The data for the current structure was taken at 119 GPa and 300 K. 
 \href{current_web_home_dir/A_oP8_62_2c-002}{oP8 Na} and \href{current_web_home_dir/A_oP8_62_2c-001}{$\alpha$-Np ($A_{c}$)} have the same AFLOW prototype label, A\_oP8\_62\_2c. They are generated by the same symmetry operations with different sets of parameters ({\tt --params}) specified in their corresponding CIF files.
